import Mathlib

/-- Definition of a Context-Free Derivation (CSD).
A CSD is a sequence of derivation steps starting from a word `u` and ending at a word `v`.
Each step is determined by a production rule from a context-free grammar `G`.
The derivation proceeds by replacing a variable with its right-hand side according to a production rule.
The derivation is represented as a binary tree where each internal node corresponds to a derivation step.
The root of the tree is the initial word `u`.
Each left child of a node corresponds to the left-hand side of the production rule used in that step.
Each right child corresponds to the right-hand side.
The derivation is exhaustive if all variables in the initial word `u` are eventually replaced.
The derivation is valid if it correctly transforms `u` into `v` according to the grammar rules.
The derivation is non-trivial if `u ≠ v`.
The derivation step is sound if it correctly applies a production rule.
-/
def ContextFreeDerivation (α : Sort u) (β : Sort v) (γ : Sort w) (δ : Sort x)
    [DecidableEq α] [DecidableEq β] [DecidableEq γ] [DecidableEq δ]
    [DecidableEq (α ⊕ β)] [DecidableEq (γ ⊕ δ)]
    (G : ContextFreeGrammar α β γ δ)
    (u v : Word (α ⊕ β)) :
    List (DerivationTree G) × (u = v → False) × (∃ (t : DerivationTree G), t.val = v) ×
    (∀ (t : DerivationTree G), t.val ≠ u → t ≠ []) ×
    (∃ (t : DerivationTree G), t.val = u) ×
    (∀ (t : DerivationTree G), t.val ≠ u → t ≠ []) :=
  ⟨List.ofFn (λ i => DerivationTree.leaf none), fun _ => by simp, ⟨DerivationTree.leaf none, by simp⟩, fun _ => by simp, ⟨DerivationTree.leaf none, by simp⟩, fun _ => by simp⟩

